 1550":"about 1550","about 1532":"about 1532","from 1527 to 1539":"from 1527 to 1539","about 1533":"about 1533","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","1626":"1626","of Swanbourne, Bucks., Eng.":"Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Aston Clinton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aston Clinton, Buckinghamshire, England","Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England":"Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kinge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  King  ."],"variants":[{"name":"King","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>king</i> ‘king’ (Old English <i>cyning</i>, <i>cyng</i>), perhaps acquired by someone with kingly qualities or as a pageant name by someone who had acted the part of a king or had been chosen as the master of ceremonies or ‘king’ of an event such as a tournament, festival or folk ritual. In North America, the surname <i>King</i> has absorbed several European cognates and equivalents with the same meaning, for example German <b>König</b> (see   Koenig  ) and <b>Küng</b>, French   Roy  , Slovenian, Croatian, or Serbian   Kralj  , Polish   Krol  . It is also very common among African Americans. It is also found as an artificial Jewish surname.","English: occasionally from the Middle English personal name <i>King</i>, originally an Old English nickname from the vocabulary word <i>cyning</i>, <i>cyng</i> ‘king’.","Irish: adopted for a variety of names containing the syllable <i>rí</i> (which means ‘king’ in Irish)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":37,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":46,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":73,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":75,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":108,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlT